STOR 455 Content: Data Analysis

This course from the UNC Department of Statistics and Operations Research focuses on the primary techniques of regression analysis. The topics include simple to multiple linear and logistic regression, matrix representation of the regression model, statistical inferences for regression model, diagnostics and remedies for multicollinearity, outlier and influential cases, polynomial regression and interaction regression models, model selection, weighted least square procedure for unequal error variances, and ANOVA model and test.

Anova: Does the model explain a significant amount of the total variability?

anova(mod1)
anova(mod_trans)

Null hypothesis: The mdoel does not explain the variablity in the data Alternate hypothesis: The model accounts for variablity, and is strong

The Sum Square/Mean Square of the residuals should be low, the F-value should be high, the P-value should be lower than 0.5 (reject the null and show the model is effective)

The F-statistic: indicates whether the linear regression model provides a better fit to the data than a model that contains no independent variables.

R-squared: proportion of total variablity that is explained by the model, shows how much more accurate the least squares line is than a model based on the mean of data.

4) Anova that is not split sequentially for each predictor

# ANOVA for Regression - formatted for whole model
# Argument: model - an lm model

anova455=function(model){
  numpred=model$rank-1
  dferror=df.residual(model)
  dfmodel=numpred
  dftotal=dfmodel+dferror
  sse=sum(model$residual^2)
  ssmodel=sum(model$effects[2:(numpred+1)]^2)
  sstotal=ssmodel+sse
  msmodel=ssmodel/dfmodel
  mse=sse/dferror
  fstat=msmodel/mse
  pvalue=1-pf(fstat,dfmodel,dferror)
  df=c(dfmodel,dferror,dftotal)
  ss=c(ssmodel,sse,sstotal)
  ms=c(msmodel,mse,0)
  f=c(fstat,0,0)
  p=c(pvalue,0,0)
  table=data.frame(df,ss,ms,f,p)
  table[2,4:5]=NA
  table[3,3:5]=NA
  
  colnames(table)=c("Df","Sum Sq","Mean Sq","F value","P(>F)")
  row.names(table)=c("Model","Error","Total")
  class(table)=c("anova","data.frame")
  structure(table,
            heading=c("ANOVA Table",
                      paste("Model:", 
                            formula(model)[2],
                            formula(model)[1],
                            formula(model)[3],"\n")
            )
  )
}


anova455(mod1)

look at p-value and f-statistic for the overall effectiveness of the model

  • F-statistic shows if there is multicolinearity in the model
  • Adding additional predictors increases SSModel, Decreases SSE, and increases Rsquared

5) VIF - Variable Inflation Factor

  • If vif is greater than 10, then there must be some kind of colinearlity
#run the code below to acivate a VIF function 
# for multiple regression models

vif<- function(model, ...) {  
  V <- summary(model)$cov.unscaled
  Vi <- crossprod(model.matrix(model))
  nam <- names(coef(model))
  if(k <- match("(Intercept)", nam, nomatch = F)) {
    v1 <- diag(V)[-k]
    v2 <- (diag(Vi)[-k] - Vi[k, -k]^2/Vi[k,k])
    nam <- nam[-k]
  } else {
    v1 <- diag(V)
    v2 <- diag(Vi)
    warning("No intercept term detected.  Results may
surprise.")
  }
  structure(v1*v2, names = nam)
}

all=regsubsets(SAT~Takers+Income+Years+Public+Expend+Rank,
        data=StateSAT,nbest=2)

#Function to show results for regsubsets
# input should be the result from regsubsets

ShowSubsets=function(regout){
  z=summary(regout)
  q=as.data.frame(z$outmat)
  q$Rsq=round(z$rsq*100,2)
  q$adjRsq=round(z$adjr2*100,2)
  q$Cp=round(z$cp,2)
  return(q)
}


ShowSubsets(all)

Mallows Cp

  • R2, Adjusted R2, SSE, all depend only on the predictors in the model being evaluated NOT the other potential predictors in the pool.
  • Cp must be small for a good set of predictors

Testing Multiple Regression Model

There are individual t-tests and anova455 model for overall fit, but there is a way to test subsets of predictors to see if they improve the model

Nested Model

  • How much do the extra predictors add to the model?
  • This is shown through a Nested F-test
#How much variability is explained by the extra predictors?
HondaReduced=lm(price~age+ I(age^2),data=Honda)
anova455(HondaReduced)
HondaFull=lm(price~age+mileage+I(mileage^2)+I(age*mileage),data=Honda)
anova455(HondaFull)
SSMnew = anova455(HondaFull)[1,2] - anova455(HondaReduced)[1,2]

MSEfull = anova455(HondaFull)[2,3]

Fstat = ((SSMnew)/3)/MSEfull

Fstat
## [1] 7.041621
1- pf(Fstat,3,46)
## [1] 0.0005406284
anova(HondaFull, HondaReduced)

null hypothesis: the reduced model is adequate alternate hypothesis: the full model is better with the quantitative and interaction variables

The F-statistic compared to an f-distribution with the p-value shows how much more significant the model is

Cross-Validation

A model may reflect the structure of a particular sample, but not generalize well to the population.

PulseTrain=Pulsef17[1:300,]       #select the training sample
PulseHoldout=Pulsef17[301:375,]   #create the holdout sample


#column of predictions
fitActive=predict(mod4,newdata=PulseHoldout)

#residuals for holdout sample
holdoutresid=PulseHoldout$Active - fitActive

#residual analysis
mean(holdoutresid)
## [1] -3.122385
sd(holdoutresid)
## [1] 12.78926

Cross Validation Correlation & Shrinkage

#correlation between actual test set and the predicted results
corr = cor(PulseHoldout$Active,fitActive)

#cross validation R2 
corr^2
## [1] 0.3669477

In ordinary regression the model predicts the mean Y for any combination of predictors.Goal of logistic regression: Predict the true proportion of success, , at any value of the predictor.

Better Form Logit glm function

Provides a deviance analysis and the estimate is the proportion of success

Comparing Logistic Models

Coefficients are chosen to minimize the sum of the squared errors in the observed sample. Overall Test null hypothesis: How much better does the linear model do than one with a constant ( mean evaluation)?

Parameters are chosen to maximize the likelihood of the observed sample. Measure likelihood through Residual Deviance

How much improvement with the predictor? G-statistic ->Want the highests G-stat, difference between the null and residual deviance -> Evaluated with chi-square test

lmodPutt=glm(Made~Length,family=binomial,data=Putts1)

null hypothesis: There is no significant difference among the means of each group alternate hypothesis: There is a significant difference among the means of each group

Which means are significantly different? -Use pairwise comparisons (means considered different at a 5% level- aka a 95% confidence interval)

Pairwise Comparisons

Anova via Dummy Regression

Create indicator predictors for each factor Run regression with the dummy predictors (leaving out one for each factor) To include interaction: Use products of the (included) dummies. How to interpret the coefficients? How to recover the three ANOVA components?

Ancova Modeling

If we can use dummy predictors to convert an ANOVA for means into a regression model, why not also include quantitative predictors?

Active = 0 + 1Rest + 2Exer1 + 3Exer2 + B0 and B1 are the Covariates and B2 and B3 are Factors

Look at the plots of One Way Anova. New condition to consider: Is there an interaction between the covariate and the factor?

PulseF17 = read.csv("/Users/abwilli/Downloads/PulseF17.csv")
#one way anova test
modp = aov(Active~factor(Exercise), data = PulseF17)
summary(modp)
##                   Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## factor(Exercise)   2  14342    7171   24.02 1.54e-10 ***
## Residuals        372 111050     299                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#Ancova model
modp2log = lm(log(Active)~Rest + factor(Exercise), data = PulseF17)
anova(modp2log)
plot(modp2log$residuals~modp2log$fitted.values)

qqnorm(modp2log$residuals)
qqline(modp2log$residuals)

#visualize interactions between covariate(Rest) and factors (exercise 1-3)
Exercise1 = subset(PulseF17, PulseF17$Exercise==1)
Exercise2 = subset(PulseF17, PulseF17$Exercise==2)
Exercise3= subset(PulseF17, PulseF17$Exercise==3)

lme1.log = lm(log(Active) ~ Rest, data=Exercise1)
lme2.log = lm(log(Active) ~ Rest, data=Exercise2)
lme3.log = lm(log(Active) ~ Rest, data=Exercise3)

plot(log(Active) ~ Rest, data=PulseF17)
abline(lme1.log)
abline(lme2.log, col='red')
abline(lme3.log, col='blue')
